{
  "text": "Late-onset focal dermal elastosis (LOFDE) is a rare disorder of elastic tissue, characterized by a PXE-like yellowish papular eruption, with local accumulation of elastic \ufffdbers in the mid-and deep reticular dermis [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . \ue062e disease occurs mainly in elderly people and typically affects the sides of the neck and \ufffdexural areas, closely mimicking PXE from the clinical point of view [CITATION_3] . \ue062e elderly onset of this disease suggests that LOFDE may be a disorder of aging. Occurrence of the lesions on the neck, antecubital and popliteal fossae is potentially signi\ufffdcant\ufffd it has been hypothesized that elastic \ufffdber turnover may be accelerated in these areas, which are naturally subjected to mechanical stress [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Isolated \ufffdbroblasts from lesional skin show increased collagen and elastin messenger RNA suggesting that the disorder may be the result of increased elastin synthesis rather than a reduction in the degradation process [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
